[normal]1.
[normal]3
[normal]  
[normal]              
[normal]It has become apparent that cycling as a mode of transport is on the increase as more road users 
[normal]are
[normal] switching 
[normal]to pedal cycle
[normal]s. This has been enhanced with the success of the British Cycling 
[normal]T
[normal]eam and 
[normal]as a more cost effective, sometimes quicker and greener way to comm
[normal]ute to work and places of 
[normal]study
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4
[normal]              
[normal]Greater Manchester is the home of British Cycling and has excellent faciliti
[normal]es within the 
[normal]Velodrome
[normal]. The 
[normal]road
[normal]s are not, proportionately, as well developed
[normal].  
[normal]              
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3
[normal]              
[normal]N
[normal]ational 
[normal]KSI 
[normal]statistics 
[normal]identify 
[normal]that whilst
[normal] overall
[normal] numbers 
[normal]of KSI’s have decreased
[normal] the 
[normal]proportion of 
[normal]pedal cyclists KSI numbers
[normal] has 
[normal]risen
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4
[normal]              
[normal]Within Greater 
[normal]Manchester t
[normal]he highest number of KSI figures in relation to pedal 
[normal]cyclists
[normal] was the main 
[normal]A34, B5117 and A6010
[normal] route from 
[normal]the south west of Manchester
[normal] to the city centre. This route 
[normal]is 
[normal]used by students using pedal power attending the University of 
[normal]              
[normal]Manchester and 
[normal]daily commuters. This route 
[normal]includes what is commonly known as ‘Curry Mile’ as the road is the centre of a plethora of late night eating houses 
[normal]used by all.
[normal]  F
[normal]rom January 2011 to August 2012 there were 43 
[normal]pedal 
[normal]cyclists’
[normal] collisions
[normal] 
[normal]on this r
[normal]oad 
[normal]4 of which were serious
[normal].
